More Diabetes Care information:&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href='http://www.diabetescarenow.com/diabetes-care/learn-about-type-1-diabetes-symptoms-associations/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: Learn About Type 1 Diabetes Symptoms Associations'&gt;Learn About Type 1 Diabetes Symptoms Associations&lt;/a&gt; &lt;small&gt; Type 1 Diabetes Symptoms Type 1 diabetes is often...&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href='http://www.diabetescarenow.com/type-1-diabetes/type-1-diabetes-insulin/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: Type 1 Diabetes Insulin'&gt;Type 1 Diabetes Insulin&lt;/a&gt; &lt;small&gt; People with Type 1 diabetes will always have it....&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href='http://www.diabetescarenow.com/diabetes-care/learn-about-sample-diabetes-meal-plan-associations/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: Learn About Sample Diabetes Meal Plan Associations'&gt;Learn About Sample Diabetes Meal Plan Associations&lt;/a&gt; &lt;small&gt; Sample Diabetes Meal Plan Diabetes is a sickness that...&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href='http://www.diabetescarenow.com/diabetes-care/top-diabetes-type-1-tips/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: Top Diabetes Type 1 Tips!'&gt;Top Diabetes Type 1 Tips!&lt;/a&gt; &lt;small&gt; The amount of sugar in our body is for...&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href='http://www.diabetescarenow.com/diabetes-mellitus/a-guide-to-diabetes-mellitus-causes-and-treatment/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: A Guide to Diabetes Mellitus Causes and Treatment'&gt;A Guide to Diabetes Mellitus Causes and Treatment&lt;/a&gt; &lt;small&gt; Diabetes mellitus, also known simply as diabetes, is becoming...&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/diabetes-care/Diabetes_Care-Learn_about_Insulin.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><center>
<p style="text-align:center;"><object width="425" height="344"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/K_WPLbr42Lw&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/K_WPLbr42Lw&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" width="425" height="344"></embed></object></p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K_WPLbr42Lw">Insulin</a></p>
<p></center>
<p>The body produces the hormone insulin, which is secreted by islet cells in the pancreas.  Carbohydrates are absorbed into the blood from the intestines after a meal.  From there, insulin is secreted by the pancreas in response to the detected glucose increase.  When insulin attaches to the surface of a cell, the cell activates other receptors that are designed to absorb the sugar from the blood. </p>
<p> If you do not have enough insulin, you can eat a large amount of food and remain in a state of starvation.  This is because many of your cells can't access the calories within the glucose very well without enough insulin.  If you're diagnosed as having Type I diabetes, then you can become very sick without insulin shots.  Insulin is an essential hormone, and those that do not have enough of it need to have it replaced thru pumps or shots. </p>
<p> Type II is commoner than Type I diabetes, however.  In Type II diabetes, folk will develop a resistance to insulin instead of a deficiency of it.  The difficulty is the cells inside of Type II diabetics make a response to the insulin their body produces in a slow way.  This is because the insulin cannot be absorbed by the cells like it should.  This can end up in glucose levels that are higher than standard.  Sometimes, people with Type II need insulin shots, but other treatments are used more often than not. </p>
<p> Insulin Treatments<br /> if you need insulin treatments, there are only a few things you need to keep in mind. <br /> Inform your doctor about other medicines you use---especially oral diabetes medicines. <br /> make sure you don't have any kidney or liver illness.  If you do, tell your GP. <br /> remember that for the treatment program to work, you want to exercise and diet. <br /> Follow your medication, diet, and exercising plan constantly. <br /> Visit your doctor often .  Your treatment program must be monitored correctly. <br /> Tell your doctor if you're pregnant, as you may need treatment for Gestational diabetes. </p>
<p> Tips on administering insulin treatments<br /> Use your medication precisely as the doctor prescribed.  Never use it in bigger amounts. <br /> Never self inject if you are not a hundred percent sure of the process, including the injection and disposal of the syringes and needles. </p>
<p> Insulin aspart is fast acting.  You need to eat a meal inside ten minutes of injecting it. <br /> Use each expendable needle just once and throw it away in a puncture-proof container. <br /> Keep the container of used needles away from children and pets. <br /> If you use any medication with an insulin pump, ensure you do not dilute or mix it with insulin aspart. <br /> If your infusion pump does not seem to be working properly, call your health practitioner right away. <br /> select a different spot on your body everytime you inject with this medicine.  Never inject into the same spot 2 times in a row. </p>
<p> Overdose alert<br /> if you experience any Problems with administering your insulin, or if you ever overdose, go to the hospital or clinic straight away.  An overdose of insulin may cause hypoglycemia, which will lead to significant Problems, for example fits, stomach discomfort, or even a coma.</p>
