      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><center>
<p style="text-align:center;"><object width="425" height="344"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/ULVHO8W4xMQ&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/ULVHO8W4xMQ&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" width="425" height="344"></embed></object></p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ULVHO8W4xMQ">Gestational Diabetes Recipes</a></p>
<p></center>
<p>Approximately five percent of all pregnant women in the US develop Gestational diabetes.  It is becoming more and more common these days as so many individuals have bad eating habits.  Even younger girls in their twenties can be diagnosed as having Gestational diabetes.  There are lots of questions pregnant girls want to know the answers to,eg what sorts of food is safe for them to eat. <br /> Well, the essential problem that causes Gestational diabetes in the 1st place is unacceptable eating habits.  Anyone who eats too many bad sugar and carbohydrates is at a risk.  Dumping plenty of sugar and carb is tough for some people, but it has got to be done in order to help treat Gestational diabetes.  The Net is stuffed with thousands of Gestational diabetes recipes that are straightforward to cook and prepare. </p>
<p> There are many paths to modify a certain recipe in order to meet an individual's private dietary wishes.  It is possible for a woman with Gestational diabetes to eat healthy foods without sacrificing flavor.  A sample diet plan is usually a good place to get started, and there are plenty of recipes that can be included with it. <br /> Here are some Gestational diabetes recipes. </p>
<p> Breakfast<br /> everyone knows that breakfast is the most crucial meal, so making a sensible choice for a breakfast recipe is essential.  It is OK, sometimes, to have one carbohydrate with a breakfast meal.  Food that is high in protein is critical, also. <br /> Some good breakfast ideas include :<br /> piece of whole grain toast with an egg<br /> tiny bowl of blueberries and a few almonds<br /> Half a banana<br /> a small amount of all natural peanut butter on a slice of whole grain bread</p>
<p> Lunch</p>
<p> there are several easy Gestational diabetes recipes that do not take long at all to prepare.  These are great selections for those that don't have all of the time required for building a lunch meal.  It is best to stick with 45 grams of carbs for a midday meal. </p>
<p> Some good lunch ideas include :</p>
<p> Bowl of fresh veggies<br /> Turkey sandwich with whole wheat bread, lettuce, and tomato<br /> tiny piece of fruit<br /> Boneless, skinless chicken fillet ( it can be prepared earlier in the day or the night before.  )<br /> Tuna</p>
<p> Dinner</p>
<p> Gestational diabetes recipes for dinner sometimes consist of foods high in protein, such as fish and steak.  Both these are free of carbs. </p>
<p> a few carbohydrates can be permitted with the grilled chicken, salmon, or tuna, however.  Some ideas include :</p>
<p> tiny serving of pasta<br /> Baked potato<br /> Sugar free yogurt<br /> 1 cup of fruit<br /> 1 cup of steamed asparagus</p>
<p> Desserts and nibbles</p>
<p> desserts and nibbles can be eaten in between meals. </p>
<p> here is a mini-cheesecake recipe that's easy to make :</p>
<p> 1 Cup of water<br /> Unflavored jello<br /> 16 oz. of softened and cubed cream cheese<br /> one spoon of vanilla extract<br /> cup of a sugar substitute<br /> two large spoons of instant sugar free pudding mix</p>
<p> sprinkle the jelly over the water and let it stand for two mins. <br /> Microwave the mix for 40-50 seconds and then stir. <br /> Let mix stand for 2 minutes. <br /> Add cream cheese cubes and stir some more. <br /> Put in mixer and blend well. <br /> Add pudding mix, vanilla extract, and the sugar substitute. <br /> decant into either muffin tins or 8' pie pan. <br /> Put into fridge until firm.</p>
