      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><center>
<p style="text-align:center;"><object width="425" height="344"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/ULVHO8W4xMQ&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/ULVHO8W4xMQ&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" width="425" height="344"></embed></object></p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ULVHO8W4xMQ">Gestational Diabetes Recipes</a></p>
<p></center>
<p>Eating right with gestational diabetes is critical.  You are not only caring for your wellbeing but also the health of your unborn child.  There are some rules that you will need to follow when following a gestational diabetes diet. </p>
<p> First of all, you'll want to eat numerous times throughout the day.  For example, six little meals throughout the day with two snacks will prove to be profitable.  Make sure that you are continually monitoring your blood glucose levels and keeping an accurate record for them.  This will help to be a guide for you and you'll start to notice patterns during the day.  For example : maybe you are dropping'low' between lunch and dinner, so meaning that you could need a break at this time. </p>
<p> A healthful recipe - There are cookery books that are available on the market today that are strictly for the gestational diabetic.  In these cookery books, you will find healthy, satisfying recipes for breakfast, lunch, dinner, nibbles, and even desserts.  Another cool place to go looking for gestational diabetes recipes is online. </p>
<p> You don't always have to follow a recipe that's just for the'pregnant' diabetic as you could use any diabetic cooking recipe.  Since gestational diabetes is generally a result of hormones that are produced during pregnancy and resemble Type 2 diabetes, maintaining aful sensible healthy} diet that is low in sugar, low in sodium, and high in proteins and vitamins is very important. </p>
<p> When you have been diagnosed as having gestational diabetes, your physician will be ready to counsel either a dietician to help'teach' you about eating healthily and diabetic cooking or at least they can point you in the right direction and give you some kind of a tenet to follow. </p>
<p> Carbohydrates, when the body breaks them down, turns into sugar.  It'd be in your best interest to follow a low carbohydrate diet and watch your carbohydrate consumption.  You will find low carbohydrate recipes across the Net as well as cookery books that are devoted to the subject.  You can still eat carbohydrates ; you do not have to eliminate them utterly, just restrict your total grams at meal time.  For example : at breakfast-consume 30g of carbs, eat a break that consists of 30g then eat a lunch that has a total of 45g of carbs and such like.  Once again, you must talk to your physician and follow his/her advice about the diet that you must be following. </p>
<p> <a href="http://www.diabetescarenow.com/delicious-diabetic-recipes"  rel='nofollow' >Diabetic recipes</a> do not have to be dull and once you learn what you can eat and how to correctly prepare a diabetic meal, you'll be well on the way to developing your own <a href="http://www.diabetescarenow.com/delicious-diabetic-recipes"  rel='nofollow' >diabetic recipes</a>.  It may appear complicated and confusing in the beginning, but in reality after you become used to it, it is actually very simple and really isn't much different than how you must have been eating prior to your diagnosis as a gestational diabetic.  And don't forget, 9 probabilities out of ten, you almost certainly already know someone that is a diabetic that will help to teach you the ins and outs of diabetic recipes and diabetic cooking.</p>
<p>Come visit us here for your three free Diabetic Diet Ebooks: <a href="http://diabeticdietzone.com/">Gestational Diabetes Recipes</a> http://diabeticdietzone.com.</p>
