      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><center>
<p style="text-align:center;"><object width="425" height="344"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/XGOebHvfQlU&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/XGOebHvfQlU&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" width="425" height="344"></embed></object></p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XGOebHvfQlU">Diabetes Menu</a></p>
<p></center>
<p>To help learn the easiest way to prepare a diabetic menu, you will find diabetic menu samples all over the internet, as well as from a dietician, from your endocrinologist etc.  The data is generally available and all you have got to do is search for it. </p>
<p> Diabetes is a serious disease and should be taken seriously.  A diabetic menu shouldn't be very different than what you were meant to be eating, prior to the diagnosis, if you were eating healthy.  Make efforts to check with your endocrinologist to establish how they recommend for you to manipulate your diet.  Some endocrinologists do need you to count fats, proteins and so on and others only need you to count your carbohydrate intake.  Your diabetic diet and menu sample should be developed after you find out this info. </p>
<p> A Sample Menu<br /> whenever you change your diet you need to inform your physician so that they know what it is that you are changing, and they can account for the changes in your health/blood sugar levels.  To begin with, a diabetic diet should be low in sugar, naturally.  This doesn't mean that you cannot eat a candy bar, you can only permit yourself to have one now and then and make sure to account for it in your daily intake.  Your diabetic menu should also be high in proteins and proteins help your body to maintain its blood sugar levels. </p>
<p> A diabetic menu sample would usually consist of 1800 calories per day and when divided out will be fifty percent starches, 30% proteins and twenty p.c. fat.  Obviously you will need to be told how to read nourishment labels and how to measure proportions properly so that your count will be correct.  By following this diet, you will help to keep your blood sugar levels more in order and in turn, your wellbeing will become better. </p>
<p> With breakfast include : one beef, 2 fruits, two breads, 2 fats, one milk and one free food.  A sample would be : one slice of toast, one egg ( soft cooked ), 2/3 cup of juice, cup of oatmeal, one cup of skimmed milk and tea. <br /> With lunch include : 2 meats, 2 breads, one plant, two fruits, two fats and a free food.  For instance you could have : 2 pieces of bread, cup of tuna, 1 cup of mixed fruit, cup of tomatoes, a tsp of marg and a cup of tea with lemon. <br /> With supper include : 3 meats, two bread, two fats and one raw vegetable.  For instance, this could be something similar to : 3 oz of stove baked chicken, a piece of bread, cup of mashed potatoes and a tossed salad with one tsp of salad dressing. </p>
<p> Just remember to keep your caloric intake at 1800 a day.  To get some different ideas about what you can eat, consult a dietician, a <a href="http://www.diabetescarenow.com/delicious-diabetic-recipes"  rel='nofollow' >diabetic recipe</a> book or do a search on the internet.  This is just a diabetic menu sample ; so remember, that you can adjust to fit your desires as long as you follow the basic suggestions.</p>
