      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><center>
<p style="text-align:center;"><object width="425" height="344"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/Lc87Xw1PYhc&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/Lc87Xw1PYhc&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" width="425" height="344"></embed></object></p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lc87Xw1PYhc">Diabetes Care</a></p>
<p></center>
<p>Diabetes is a major disease even though it can be controlled through the employment of medication, insulin or healthy lifestyle decisions.  There are such a lot of different complications to diabetes that diabetes care is very important to every diabetic person out there who has to live with this disease each day. </p>
<p> Special Diabetes Care - to start with it is extremely critical that a person who is diabetic monitor their blood glucose levels on a constant basis.  This usually means many times during the day.  Customarily the best times to watch your levels are at meals and before bed time at night.  By keeping an accurate account of your blood glucose levels, you'll be able to narrow down what works best for you and what does not and you will be able to keep your blood glucose levels at a healthy level. </p>
<p> routinely the scale is eighty to 120.  If your levels are higher than this, relying on what type of diabetes you have, you might need to take insulin to lower your levels.  If your blood glucose level is below 80, you'll need to eat a carbohydrate and a protein to make sure that your levels will rise ( caused by the carbohydrate ) and stay there ( due to the protein ).  If you notice that your blood glucose levels vary out of control, you could need to modify your diet or your medication or maybe your insulin scale.  This is why monitoring your blood glucose levels on a regular basis is highly critical. </p>
<p> As a diabetic, you will want to get an annual eye examination.  Diabetic retinopathy is a serious condition that if not controlled can lead to blindness.  Generally a consequence of out of control blood glucose levels, diabetic retinopathy is where tiny blood vessels in the eye burst.  Inform the Ophthalmologist that you're a diabetic and they can keep correct records to refer to each year to see exactly how your eyes have changed. </p>
<p> Circulation, especially in the extremities, is another serious problem in diabetics.  Making sure that you have good circulation to your legs and feet is extremely vital.  There are special diabetic shoes and socks that can help help you in this process.  Ensure that you keep a close watch on any sores that can develop on your feet.  Diabetics tend to heal slowly and these sores can cause the amputation of toes, feet and even your leg. </p>
<p> Kidney issues are another side effect of diabetes and you really need to keep a close watch on this also.  Later in life you will need dialysis.  You can help to stop all of these discussed side-effects by maintaining your blood glucose levels in the specified range and by eating healthy and continuing with an exercise program to the best of your capabilities.   Visiting an endocrinologist on a constant basis is in your own interest.  They can help to lead you through this process to guarantee that you will lead a long, healthy life with as few complications as possible.</p>
