      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><center>
<p style="text-align:center;"><object width="425" height="344"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/DCJAkrPbkWw&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/DCJAkrPbkWw&#038;hl=en&#038;fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" width="425" height="344"></embed></object></p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DCJAkrPbkWw">ADA Guidelines</a></p>
<p></center>
<p>The American Diabetes association is naturally the leader in diabetes education, information and research.  They help to pay for research and then publish their findings so that medical execs and diabetics alike have the correct info that's wanted to better care for themselves or their patients. </p>
<p> The Yankee Diabetes association has developed a group of guidelines that helps consultants to diagnose the many different types of diabetes that a patient can have.  The guidelines also offer the latest information and goals that diabetic patients need to maintain with their blood glucose levels as well as information that the consultants need to help guide their patients in the right care and techniques for diabetes. <br /> Examples of ADA guiding principles - In 2008, the guiding principle for proper blood glucose levels was 70-130mg/dL before meals and less than 180 mg/dL after meals.  This is typically a guideline for adult diabetics as they allow children to maintain higher blood glucose levels. </p>
<p> In 2007, the suggestion for diabetes diagnosis is that the patient must have a random plasma glucose level of over 200 mg/dL at least twice before a diagnosis could be made ; although with the 2008 ADA guidelines, now you only have to have one random plasma glucose level of over 200 mg/dL before it is suggest to diagnose a patient as a diabetic. <br /> These guiding principles are set fundamentally for everything.  There are rules for pre diabetes diagnosis.  There are guiding principles for suggest A1c test results that are needed.  ( The hemoglobin A1c test results should be less that 7% is the ADA guideline.  This fundamentally means a blood glucose level of 170 mg/dL or less is commended.  The A1c test is largely a median of blood glucose levels over a 3 month period of time.</p>
<p> Carbohydrate intake is the key in maintaining blood glucose level control according to the ADA axioms.  Carbohydrates when broken down by the body turn into sugar.  Diabetic patients should limit their carbohydrate intake thru carbohydrate counting, exchanges or experience-based guesstimating.  This seems complex while it is really pretty easy once you get the grasp of the tenet and it is an excellent idea for eating healthily for all patients and not just diabetics.  ADA guidelines for carbohydrate intake are 130 grams per day. </p>
<p> The final Word - The Yankee Diabetes organisation publishes these guidelines on a regular scheduled} basis as research and newly developed info can change from year to year.  They serve as only a guiding principle to the physicians and health care providers. </p>
<p> consultants and medicare suppliers can take it upon themselves to adjust the rules to fit the wants of their patients.  Diabetes is affecting different patients in different techniques ; therefore it is hard to say that one set of numbers should work for everyone or this certain thing should do the trick.  Sadly, it doesn't work that way.  Health care providers know their patients and can adjust to fit the patients individual needs ; therefore actually providing better results than if they followed the ADA guidelines precisely.</p>
<p>Come visit us here for your three free Diabetic Diet Ebooks: <a href="http://diabeticdietzone.com/">ADA Guidelines</a> http://diabeticdietzone.com.</p>
