      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It can be difficult to self-diagnose if you have diabetes.  There are many symptoms that may mean diabetes, but they may also be symptoms of other non-diabetic diseases or problems. </p>
<p><a title="eye chart" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/28473961@N02/2761594286/" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft" style="border: 0px initial initial;" title="Symptons of Diabetes" src="http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3095/2761594286_719f6dcde1_m.jpg" border="0" alt="eye chart" width="240" height="180" /></a></p>
<p>Conversely, many symptoms of diabetes may be ignored because they seem unimportant.  Ignoring symptoms of diabetes can have terrible consequences.  It is important to schedule an appointment with your doctor right away to either rule out diabetes or confirm it.  The sooner you treat diabetes, the better you will be.</p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>Symptons of diabetes may include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Blindness</li>
<li>Excessive number of infections</li>
<li>Excessive thirst</li>
<li>Excessive tiredness</li>
<li>Extreme dry skin</li>
<li>Extreme hunger</li>
<li>Frequent urination</li>
<li>Hair loss</li>
<li>Heart Attack</li>
<li>Impotence</li>
<li>Irritability</li>
<li>Kidney failure</li>
<li>Nerve damage</li>
<li>Slow healing sores </li>
<li>Stroke</li>
<li>Sudden vision changes </li>
<li>Teeth and gum problems</li>
<li>Tingling or numbness in your feet or hands </li>
<li>Toe, foot, or leg infections</li>
<li>Unexplained weight loss </li>
</ul>
<p>If you suspect that you may have diabetes, then do not wait to see your doctor to find out for sure.  The sooner you are diagnosed and treated for diabetes, then the sooner you will feel better.</p>
