      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div style="float:left; padding: 12px"><a href="/wp-content/uploads/2009/03/diabetes4.jpg"><img src="/wp-content/uploads/2009/03/diabetes4.jpg" alt="" /></a></div>
<p>If diabetes runs in your family then you may wonder, "How high are my risks for getting diabetes?"  It is a good question to ponder.</p>
<p>The truth is, diabetes is known to be a hereditary disease.  This means, if members of your family are diabetic, then there is a greater chance that you, too, will also become diabetic.</p>
<p>There are three things you can do to help minimize your chance of developing diabetes:</p>
<p><strong>Exercise</strong></p>
<p>Regular exercise will do wonders for you, regardless if you are at risk for diabetes.  Try to get at least 20 minutes of exercise, four days a week.  Take the stairs instead of the elevator to get to work.  Pass over the spot right in front of the grocery store and park farther away, forcing yourself to walk a bit further than you normally would.</p>
<p><strong>Eat a Healthy Diet</strong></p>
<p>Plan meals that are well-balanced and include a lot of protein, fresh fruits, and fresh vegetables.  When you get hungry in between meals, reach for an apple or orange instead of a cookie.</p>
<p><strong>Maintain your Weight</strong></p>
<p>Obesity is a big factor when it comes to developing diabetes.  Watch your weight and keep it in the ideal range for your height.  </p>
<p>These are things we should all be doing anyway, but it is especially important for people who are have a hereditary risk of getting diabetes.</p>
