      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="anna" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/63415923@N00/3263488503/" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft" style="border: 0px initial initial;" title="For juvenile diabetes" src="http://farm1.static.flickr.com/193/3263488503_4b4af8b0c6_m.jpg" border="0" alt="anna" width="180" height="240" /></a>There is a lot of information available aimed at parents <a href="http://www.diabetescarenow.com/juvenile-diabetes/for-juvenile-diabetes/" >for juvenile diabetes</a> education.  This is can be very helpful, as it helps parents of diabetic children find other people going through what they are going through.</p>
<p>It is easy to feel alone when dealing with a sick child.  Fortunately, the Internet provides forums, discussion groups, and blogs that invite these parents to join their communities.</p>
<p>One such blog is <a href="http://juvenilediabetessymptoms.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">Living With Juvenile Diabetes Symptoms</a>, which is a blog written by a mother who has four children, two of whom have type 1 diabetes.</p>
