      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="Ya no queda nada" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/24175071@N00/3352437508/" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft" style="border: 0px initial initial;" title="Diabetes of pregnancy" src="http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3634/3352437508_9d9a722cc4_m.jpg" border="0" alt="Ya no queda nada" width="240" height="180" /></a>When a pregnant woman's blood glucose levels become too high, she will develop <a href="http://www.diabetescarenow.com/gestational-diabetes/diabetes-of-pregnancy/" >diabetes of pregnancy</a>, commonly known as gestational diabetes.  This can be scary, but for most moms, the diabetes disappears after giving birth.</p>
<p>One of the problems of gestational diabetes is that the developing baby becomes too large, causing a difficult delivery.  It is also typical for babies born to mothers with gestational diabetes to be born with low blood glucose.  </p>
<p>It is important for pregnant women with diabetes to carefully monitor what they eat.  They can enlist the help of a registered dietician to make sure they are eating properly, both for their health and the health of their unborn babies.  Diets low in sugar are very important.</p>
